div.p: Transcribing this text for papyri.info required a number of departures from the critical edition of Azzarello 2019, principally as regards the handling of the small oblique strokes (or â€˜ticksâ€™) that accompany whole numbers and fractions on papyri. Where Azzarelloâ€™s text supplements these (if they are missing), and expunges them (if they were added superfluously), papyri.info is unable to render these â€˜ticksâ€™ within angled or curly brackets. The text transcribed here, therefore, is that of the papyrus: where a tick is present on the papyrus â€“ even in error â€“ it is encoded; when one is absent it is not, even if the number is a fraction and would normally be expected to include one. The exception to this practice is where ticks are marked on the papyrus beside each digit in a double or triple-digit fraction (e.g., col. i.4 where Î»Â´ ÎµÂ´ = 1/35): in such cases, papyri.info can only render a single tick even if two appear on the papyrus (Î»ÎµÂ´ instead of Î»Â´ ÎµÂ´). The commentary notes other curiosities involving ticks.
The first two columns are preserved by SB 20 15071; the rest are on P.Mich. 3 146.
